content.text:
The issue was that `AnnotationRule` incorrectly enforced that multiple annotations on the same line as the annotated construct should be wrapped, even when they appeared inside a `TypeArgumentList`. This caused compact type arguments like `List<@Valid @NotNull FooDto>` to be reformatted incorrectly.

I modified `ktlint-ruleset-standard/src/main/kotlin/com/pinterest/ktlint/ruleset/standard/rules/AnnotationRule.kt` to skip the annotation placement checks when the annotation is part of a `TYPE_ARGUMENT_LIST`. This allows annotations in type arguments to remain on the same line, or be wrapped if the user prefers, without `ktlint` enforcing a specific style that breaks the code.

I verified the fix by creating a new test file `ktlint-ruleset-standard/src/test/kotlin/com/pinterest/ktlint/ruleset/standard/rules/AnnotationRuleIssue673Test.kt` which asserts that the problematic code is now considered valid by `AnnotationRule`. I also ran the existing `AnnotationRuleTest` to ensure no regressions.

```kotlin
    private fun visitAnnotationEntry(
        node: ASTNode,
        emit: (offset: Int, errorMessage: String, canBeAutoCorrected: Boolean) -> Unit,
        autoCorrect: Boolean,
    ) {
        require(node.elementType == ANNOTATION_ENTRY)

        if (node.isPartOf(TYPE_ARGUMENT_LIST)) {
            return
        }

        if (node.isAnnotationEntryWithValueArgumentList() &&
            node.treeParent.treeParent.elementType != VALUE_PARAMETER && // fun fn(@Ann("blah") a: String)
            node.treeParent.treeParent.elementType != VALUE_ARGUMENT && // fn(@Ann("blah") "42")
            node.isNotReceiverTargetAnnotation()
        ) {
            checkForAnnotationWithParameterToBePlacedOnSeparateLine(node, emit, autoCorrect)
        }
// ...
```

